          "body": "The chapter returns twice to an identical purpose clause: the tabernacle 'will be a unit' (echad, vv.6, 11). The word echad — the same word used of the LORD Himself in the Shema (Deuteronomy 6:4) — describes the structural goal of both the inner and outer curtain assemblies. Fifty loops on each edge, fifty clasps to join them: the precision is not architectural pedantry but covenantal symbolism. Fifty is the number of Jubilee (Leviticus 25:10-11) — freedom, completeness, divine fullness. The tabernacle is unified by a system that is simultaneously exact (fifty loops, fifty clasps, perfectly opposed, v.5) and gracious (the gold clasps are provided by God's specification, not improvised by Israel). The structural unity of the tabernacle pictures the relational unity God is building with Israel: a diverse assembly (twelve tribes) brought together under one covering, meeting one God, united by His design. Swindoll notes that the precision of the tabernacle's construction is the OT counterpart to Paul's imagery of the body of Christ in 1 Corinthians 12 — many parts, one body, each fitted to the other by the Designer's intent."
