          "title": "Built on atonement — the silver foundations",
          "body": "The frames of the tabernacle's walls rest in silver bases (vv.19, 21, 25) — eighty silver bases under forty frames for the north and south walls, sixteen under eight frames for the west wall. Exodus 38:25-28 identifies the source of this silver: it was cast from the half-shekel atonement-ransom collected from every Israelite male in the census of Numbers 1. The tabernacle literally stands on the ransom-price of Israel's souls. Every priest who ever entered the Holy Place stepped on the foundation of expiation — the price paid for the right of a guilty people to have God among them. No one could enter the tabernacle without standing, unknowingly, on the evidence that they had been ransomed. This detail, embedded in the plain measurement-language of verse 19, is one of the Old Testament's most quietly powerful atonement-statements: the place where God dwells among sinners is founded on the price of their redemption."
